Claims CLAIMS: 1. A system comprising: a display; a processor; memory storing instructions configured to cause the processor to: receive a request to scale one or more objects of on a model depicted on the display; identify the one or more objects of the model; determine one or more model parameters of the model, wherein the model parameters comprise information indicative of the one or more objects, the model, the display, or any combination thereof; calculate a size for the one or more objects of the model based on the one or more model parameters; and scale the one or more objects based on the size for the objects. 2. The system of claim 1, wherein the one or more objects comprise one or more annotations, wherein the one or more annotations provide information indicative of one or more features of the one or more objects, and wherein the one or more annotations comprise text, one or more graphics, one or more tables, or any combination thereof displayed on the model. 3. The system of claim 1, wherein the model comprises a portion of the one or more objects visible via the display, wherein the portion of the objects visible via the display is bound by one or more borders of the display. 4. The system of claim 1, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to identify the one or more objects comprises manually receiving an input configured to identify the one or more objects. 5. The system of claim 1, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to identify the one or more objects comprises automatically identifying the one or more objects depicted via the display. 6. The system of claim 1, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to calculate the size for the one or more objects comprises determining at least two dimensions of the display and determining the size for the one or more objects based at least in part on the at least two dimensions of the display. 7. The system of claim 1, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to calculate the size for the one or more objects comprises: determining whether a number of the one or more objects displayed on the model exceed a threshold; and determining a respective size of a respective each of the one or more objects when the number exceeds the threshold. 8. The system of claim 7, wherein the threshold comprises a first number indicative of a second number of objects identified on the display or a third number indicative of a fourth number of objects identified per unit area of the display. 9. The system of claim 1, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to scale the one or more objects comprises adjusting a respective size of each of the one or more objects of the model based on the size. 10. A method, comprising: receiving, via a processor, a request via a user interface to scale one or more objects of on a model depicted on a display; identifying, via the processor, the one or more objects of the model; 

 determining, via the processor, one or more model parameters of the model, wherein the one or more model parameters comprise information indicative of the one or more objects, the model, the display, or any combination thereof; calculating, via the processor, a size for the one or more objects of the model based on the one or more model parameters; and scaling, via the processor, the one or more objects based on the size for the objects. 11. The method of claim 10, wherein identifying the one or more objects comprises automatically identifying a portion of the one or more objects visible via the display, wherein the portion of the object visible via the display is bound by one or more borders of the display. 12. The method of claim 10, wherein calculating the size for the one or more objects is based at least on one or more dimensions of the display. 13. The method of claim 10, wherein calculating the size for the one or more objects comprises: determining whether a number of the one or more objects displayed on the model are less than a threshold; and determining the size of a respective each of the one or more objects when the number is less than the threshold. 14. The method of claim 10, calculating the size for the one or more objects comprises: determining whether a number of the one or more objects displayed on the model exceed a threshold; and 

 determining the size of a respective each of the one or more objects when the number exceeds the threshold. 15. The method of claim 10, wherein scaling the one or more objects based on the size for the one or more objects comprises uniformly scaling the one or more objects identified on the display. 16. A tangible, non-transitory, and computer-readable medium having instructions stored thereon that, when executed by one or more processors of a computer-aided design (CAD) system, are configured to cause the one or more processors to: receive a request to scale one or more objects of on a model depicted on a display; identify the one or more objects of the model; determine one or more model parameters of the model, wherein the model parameters comprise information indicative of the one or more objects, the model, the display, or any combination thereof; calculate a size for the one or more objects of the model based on the one or more model parameters; and scale the one or more objects based on the size for the one or more objects. 17. The tangible, non-transitory, and computer-readable medium of claim 16, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to identify the one or more objects comprises automatically identifying the one or more objects depicted via the display. 18. The tangible, non-transitory, and computer-readable medium of claim 16, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to determine the one or more model parameters comprise determining one or more dimensions of the display, a first number of characters of each of the one or more objects, a second number of the one or more objects per unit area, a view of the model, or any combination thereof. 19. The tangible, non-transitory, and computer-readable medium of claim 18, wherein the one or more dimensions of the display comprise a length and width of the display. 20. The tangible, non-transitory, and computer-readable medium of claim 16, wherein the instructions that cause the processor to calculate the size for the one or more objects comprises: determining whether a number of the one or more objects displayed on the model exceeds a threshold; and determining the size of a respective each of the one or more objects when the number exceeds the threshold.
